INS-W_963.name: Gabriella Lin
INS-W_963.description: Gabriella Lin is a 20-year-old Asian American woman of first-generation college status. She comes from a low-income family and currently lives with her mother. Gabriella attends a large public university and was previously a medical student but is taking a year out from her studies. She works part-time, including recent experience waitressing at a restaurant owned by a family friend, to help support herself financially. Gabriella is single and manages her responsibilities largely on her own, without much social support.

INS-W_1044.name: Lucy Sutton
INS-W_1044.description: Lucy Sutton is a 21-year-old single female undergraduate student currently pursuing a degree in computer science at a large urban university in the United States. She immigrated to the U.S. from Eastern Europe with her family when she was 13 years old. Lucy is fluent in English and has been living in the U.S. for about 8 years. She resides off-campus in shared housing with friends located close to her university. To help cover her living and educational expenses, Lucy works part-time at the university’s IT help desk. Additionally, she depends on scholarships and student financial aid. Her family remains in the U.S., though she does not live with them currently.

INS-W_1077.name: Alison Daniels
INS-W_1077.description: Alison Daniels is a 38-year-old Black or African American woman and a second-generation immigrant. She lives in an urban, diverse community. Alison is divorced and currently in a long-term relationship. She works as a retail sales worker at a supermarket, though her job has recently become unstable due to workplace changes. Alison is a mother to two children: a daughter aged 11 and a son aged 9. She balances her cultural heritage with the demands of her family and work life. Alison’s household experiences financial pressures typical of working-class families. She faces challenges accessing culturally sensitive mental health services that address her unique needs.
